<methodology slug="template-design">
  <metadata>
    <tier>solo</tier>
    <group>sdd</group>
    <domain>sdd-planning</domain>
    <summary>Template for design.md: HOW are we building it? Covers Architecture Decisions (ADR), Components, Data Flow, Data Models, API Endpoints, Files, Testing, Risks, FR Coverage.</summary>
    <tags>
      <tag>design</tag>
      <tag>template</tag>
      <tag>architecture</tag>
      <tag>adr</tag>
      <tag>fr-coverage</tag>
    </tags>
    <category>design</category>
    <difficulty>intermediate</difficulty>
    <created>2026-04-28</created>
  </metadata>
  <content>
    <title>Template: Design Document</title>
    <summary>A fill-in-the-blanks template for design.md — the document that answers "HOW are we building it?" after spec.md is approved. Covers Reference Documents, Overview, Architecture Decisions (AD-X in ADR format), Components, Data Flow, Data Models, API Endpoints, Files (CREATE/MODIFY), Testing Strategy, Risks, and FR Coverage table.</summary>
    <why>
      <p>Design docs without a fixed structure cause structural drift between features: some have FR Coverage tables, others do not; some ADs include Consequences, others skip them. A shared template enforces completeness — every required section is present — and makes review automatable (section presence checks, AD count, FR traceability).</p>
    </why>
    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>After spec.md is approved and before writing implementation-plan.md</item>
        <item>Generating a new design.md for any feature driven by approved requirements</item>
        <item>Reviewing an existing design doc for structural completeness against required sections</item>
        <item>Calibrating output format when a new design-writing agent is added to the pipeline</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>
    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Before spec.md is approved — template fields will be guesswork without grounded requirements</item>
        <item>For a task that affects a single file — full design doc overhead is unjustified; write the task directly</item>
        <item>As a living document — design.md should be frozen after approval; use task files for implementation details</item>
        <item>As a substitute for contracts.md — API endpoints belong in contracts, not in design</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>
    <section name="required-sections">
      <rule>
        <statement>Every design.md must contain all nine required sections: Reference Documents, Overview, Architecture Decisions, Components, Data Flow, Files, Testing Strategy, Risks, and FR Coverage.</statement>
        <rationale>Missing sections cause executor agents to make ungrounded implementation decisions. The FR Coverage table in particular must be generated last as a completeness check.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <list>
        <item>Reference Documents — links to spec.md, constitution.md, contracts.md</item>
        <item>Overview — 2-3 sentences of technical approach (write LAST, after all sections are complete)</item>
        <item>Architecture Decisions — AD-X in ADR format (minimum 3, maximum 7 for typical features)</item>
        <item>Components — component name, purpose, location, dependencies</item>
        <item>Data Flow — Component A to B to C with validation, transformation, persistence steps</item>
        <item>Files — CREATE/MODIFY/DELETE table with Action, File, Description, FR, AD columns</item>
        <item>Testing Strategy — unit tests table and integration tests table</item>
        <item>Risks — Impact, Probability, Mitigation for each risk</item>
        <item>FR Coverage — every FR-X from spec mapped to AD-X and file entries</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="ad-format">
      <rule>
        <statement>Each AD must include Context, Options (minimum 2 alternatives), Decision, Rationale, and Traces to FR-X. Omitting any field makes the AD unusable for future agents making related decisions.</statement>
        <rationale>Future agents reading a design.md need to understand why a path was NOT taken, not just what was chosen. Consequences and rejection reasons are the most valuable fields.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <example type="good" title="Minimal correct AD structure">
        <code lang="markdown"><![CDATA[### AD-1: {Decision Name}

**Context:** {Problem being solved and relevant context}

**Options:**
- **A: {Option}** — Pros: {benefits}. Cons: {drawbacks}.
- **B: {Option}** — Pros: {benefits}. Cons: {drawbacks}.

**Decision:** {Chosen solution}

**Rationale:** {Why this solution; which constraints drove the choice}

**Traces to:** FR-001, NFR-002]]></code>
      </example>
      <antipattern>
        <description>AD with straw-man alternatives — obviously inferior options listed to justify the pre-decided choice.</description>
        <reason>Agents reviewing the design cannot trust the alternatives analysis and will re-open closed decisions during implementation.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>
    <section name="fill-order">
      <rule>
        <statement>Write Overview last, after all other sections are complete. Fill FR Coverage as the final reconciliation step.</statement>
        <rationale>Overview written first becomes a summary of assumptions. Overview written last summarizes actual decisions. FR Coverage generated last catches any FR that was not assigned to an AD or file during drafting.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <list>
        <item>1. Reference Documents</item>
        <item>2. Architecture Decisions</item>
        <item>3. Components</item>
        <item>4. Data Flow</item>
        <item>5. Data Models</item>
        <item>6. API Endpoints (reference contracts.md — do not redefine)</item>
        <item>7. Files table</item>
        <item>8. Testing Strategy</item>
        <item>9. Risks</item>
        <item>10. FR Coverage (reconciliation)</item>
        <item>11. Overview (summary of actual decisions)</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="api-endpoints-rule">
      <rule>
        <statement>If contracts.md exists, the API Endpoints section must say "See contracts.md section X" and must not redefine endpoints.</statement>
        <rationale>Redefining endpoints in design.md creates two sources of truth that drift apart. Executor agents implement from design.md and produce code that diverges from the actual contract.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="antipatterns">
      <antipattern>
        <description>Writing Overview before Architecture Decisions.</description>
        <reason>Overview becomes a summary of intentions, not decisions. Write it last.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Data Models section omits constraints column.</description>
        <reason>Missing constraints cause migration failures when the executor agent implements the schema.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Files table missing test files.</description>
        <reason>Agents stop after source files. Tests must be explicit CREATE entries or they will not be implemented.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>
    <section name="checklist">
      <p>Checklist for filling the design.md template across 12 phases from document preparation through approval, with quality gate conditions.</p>
      <list>
        <item>Phase 1: Prepare — create file, fill metadata, link to spec.md and constitution.md, write Overview LAST</item>
        <item>Phase 2: Architecture Decisions — for each decision: create AD-NNN with Context, Options (min 2), Decision, Rationale, Traces to FR-X</item>
        <item>Phase 3: Components — identify components, for each: name, purpose, location, dependencies; show interactions</item>
        <item>Phase 4: Data Flow — describe A to B to C flow; show validation, transformation, persistence; document error handling</item>
        <item>Phase 5: Data Models — for each entity: fields, types, constraints; show relationships; document validation rules</item>
        <item>Phase 6: API Endpoints — reference contracts.md (do NOT redefine); create table with Method, Path, Description, FR</item>
        <item>Phase 7: Files Table — action table with File, Action (CREATE/MODIFY/DELETE), Description, FR, AD; include test files and migrations</item>
        <item>Phase 8: Testing Strategy — unit tests and integration tests; list components/functions to test; define end-to-end flows</item>
        <item>Phase 9: Risks — identify technical, dependency, and other risks; for each: Impact, Probability, Mitigation</item>
        <item>Phase 10: FR Coverage — table mapping FR | AD | Files | Status; verify every FR in spec appears in at least one AD</item>
        <item>Phase 11: Quality Gate — all required sections, AD decisions with context/options/rationale, FR coverage mapped, components documented, data models with constraints, API endpoints reference contracts, files include tests, testing covers happy path and errors, risks identified and mitigated, no code snippets</item>
        <item>Phase 12: Approval — mark status explicitly (Draft / Review / Approved) and do not modify after Approved</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="best-practices">
      <list>
        <item>Fill the FR Coverage table last — it catches missed requirements that were not assigned to any AD or file during drafting</item>
        <item>Write each AD as a standalone mini-ADR: someone reading only that AD must understand the full decision context</item>
        <item>"Consequences" subsection in each AD is the most valuable part for future agents — do not skip it</item>
        <item>Keep the Files table synchronized with the implementation plan; drift here causes task conflicts</item>
        <item>API Endpoints section must say "See contracts.md" if contracts.md exists — never redefine endpoints</item>
        <item>Mark design status explicitly (Draft / Review / Approved) and do not modify after Approved</item>
        <item>Version bump design.md if significant changes are needed post-approval; link old version in git history</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="ai-agent-gotchas">
      <list>
        <item>Agents generate AD-1, AD-2 labels but start content with AD-001 in body — use consistent numbering</item>
        <item>"Alternatives Considered" tables are frequently filled with straw men (obviously inferior options) rather than real alternatives — reviewer must check</item>
        <item>Data Models section: agents omit constraint column, which causes migration failures when executor implements</item>
        <item>Agents write "See spec.md" in Overview instead of summarizing — Overview must add technical context, not just reference</item>
        <item>Template's component diagram placeholder causes agents to insert ASCII art — replace with a description or directory tree</item>
        <item>Files table misses test files — agents stop after source files; tests are required entries</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <templates>
      <template path="templates/design.md" purpose="Complete design.md template with all required sections and placeholder text"/>
      <template path="templates/design-section-check.py" purpose="Verifies required sections present and counts ADs and FR traces"/>
    </templates>
